<subSubSection pageId="103" pageNumber="104" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="103.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,332,357]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Remarks.</emphasis>
The present material conforms to previous descriptions of this species (
<bibRefCitation author="Schmidt" box="[1133,1302,332,357]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" refString="Schmidt, O. (1880) Die Spongien des Meerbusen von Mexico (Und des caraibischen Meeres). Heft II. Abtheilung II." type="journal volume" year="1880">Schmidt, 1880</bibRefCitation>
; Zea, 1986; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kelly-Borges" box="[151,428,367,392]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" refString="Kelly-Borges, M., Robinson, E. V., Gunasekera, S. P., Gunasekera, M., Gulavita, N. K. &amp; Pomponi, S. A. (1994) Species differentiation in the marine sponge genus Discodermia (Demospongiae: Lithistida): the utility of ethanol extract profiles as species-specific chemotaxonomic markers. Biochemical Systematics and Ecology, 22, 353 - 365." type="journal article" year="1994">
Kelly-Borges 
<emphasis box="[308,364,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">et al.</emphasis>
1994
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pomponi" box="[440,669,367,392]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" refString="Pomponi, S. A., Kelly, M., Reed, J. K. &amp; Wright, A. E. (2001) Diversity and bathymetric distribution of lithistid sponges in the tropical western Atlantic. Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 10, 344 - 353." type="journal article" year="2001">
Pomponi 
<emphasis box="[548,603,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">et al.</emphasis>
2001
</bibRefCitation>
; Moraes, 2011; Van Soest 
<emphasis box="[964,1019,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">et al.</emphasis>
2014; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pisera" box="[1096,1375,367,392]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" refString="Pisera, A. &amp; Pomponi, S. A. (2015) New data on lithistid sponges from the deep Florida shelf with description of a new species of Theonella. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom, 95 (7), 1297 - 1309." type="journal article" year="2015">Pisera &amp; Pomponi, 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The species shows a depth related variation in density of the desma skeleton, with few and thin desmas and discotriaenes in shallow-water specimens resulting in a remarkable compressibility, whereas deep-water species have proper stony lithistid skeletons with dense cover of discotriaenes overlying a strongly zygosed desma skeleton. It is as yet unverified if these skeletal variations are also reflected in the habit. Deep-water specimens appear to be more often finger-shaped, whereas shallow-water specimens tend to occur in dense, closely adhering clusters of lobes [compare shallow-water specimens depicted in 
<bibRefCitation author="Zea" box="[888,1013,584,608]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" refString="Zea, S. (1987) Esponjas del Caribe Colombiano. Catalogo Cientific, Bogot, Colombia, 286 pp." type="book" year="1987">Zea (1987)</bibRefCitation>
(p. 265) and Moraes (2011) (p. 115) with the deep-water specimens in Van Soest 
<emphasis box="[651,707,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">et al.</emphasis>
(2014) (fig. 21c) and the present (
<figureCitation box="[1091,1175,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 63" captionStartId="102.[151,250,1423,1445]" captionTargetBox="[153,1438,373,1407]" captionTargetId="figure@102.[153,1438,373,1407]" captionTargetPageId="102" captionText="FIGURE 63. Discodermia dissoluta Schmidt, 1880, a, habitus of RMNH 9787 (scale bar = 1 cm), b, SEM image of desma skeleton, c – g, SEM images of spicules, c, oxeote, c 1, details of c, d, discotriaenes, e, large acanthomicroxea, f, middle-sized acanthomicroxea, g, microrhabd, g 1, enlarged image of g." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273014/files/figure.png" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Fig. 63</figureCitation>
a)].
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="103.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">
The species is also widely known for its possession of rich bacterial populations (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Bruck" box="[1220,1429,655,680]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" refString="Bruck, W. M., Sennett, S. H., Pomponi, S. A., Willenz, P. &amp; McCarthy, P. J. (2008) Identification of the bacterial symbiont Entotheonella sp. in the mesohyl of the marine sponge Discodermia sp. The ISME Journal, 2, 335 - 339." type="journal article" year="2008">
Brück 
<emphasis box="[1299,1359,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
) apparently responsible for the production of anticancer substances discodermolides and discodermide (Gunasakera 
<emphasis box="[151,207,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">et al.</emphasis>
1990, 1991).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
